{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"Two gate defects this cycle (no_repo_root code-root drop; the prompted-structured verifier emitting an unschema'd shape that tolerant-parse silently dropped to empty → all findings `no-verification`) shared a root pattern: **a load-bearing contract between stages was implicit and only weakly enforced**, so a break degraded silently instead of failing loudly, and our tests could not catch it without brittle grep/glob/string heuristics. This story closes that CLASS for plan-review and the other LLM workflows.\n\n## Why\n- The Pass-2-verify → Pass-3-decide contract (\"each finding gets a verification keyed by integer `index`\") was implicit; a verifier returning a divergent shape produced an EMPTY-but-valid object (extra keys ignored at the Pydantic boundary), so the failure was invisible until findings mysteriously all went `no-verification`.\n- The code-read-root contract (which snapshot a stage reads) was threaded ad-hoc across five hops and silently became `None` (the det-floor P2 `no_repo_root` abstain).\n- Current gate self-tests lean on greps/globs/string-contains (e.g. the module-size allowlist↔doc lock-step, stale-path sweeps), which are brittle and miss structural breaks.\nWe want STRONG, EXPLICIT, TESTABLE contracts at the stage seams — so a break is a loud, deterministic TEST failure (and a loud runtime SIGNAL), not a silent degrade.\n\n## Posture (user-directed): expand-contract — close the TESTING gap; do NOT change production outcomes\nThis story closes the testing gap WITHOUT changing the live gate's behavior. Production verdicts/decisions/findings/parse outcomes are UNCHANGED. The only runtime additions are additive OBSERVABILITY (a loud ERROR log + a coverage counter surfaced only WHEN a contract violation is detected — the clean path stays byte-identical, so attestation/signatures are unaffected). The strict enforcement (extra=forbid parse, distinct decide reason) is PINNED BY TESTS and documented as a one-line future flip; it is NOT enabled on the live path here.\n\n## What (research-informed; authorized to research OSS). SEQUENCED — research gates the pattern; each seam is an independently-mergeable thin slice.\n\n**Phase 1 — Research (gates the pattern).** Research popular, actively-maintained OSS that run multi-stage LLM/agent pipelines + structured-output contracts (candidates, not prescriptive: Pydantic AI, Instructor, Outlines/Guidance, LangGraph/LangChain runnable schemas, DSPy signatures, Marvin, BAML, Guardrails) for how they (a) make inter-stage contracts explicit, (b) fail loudly on contract drift, (c) test the seams without string heuristics. Capture findings + cited patterns in `docs/adr/`; record the adopted pattern BEFORE Phase-2 is finalized.\n\n**Phase 2 — Pass-2→Pass-3 verification contract (thin slice, deterministic negative test).**\n  * Provide a STRICT verification-contract validator (extra=forbid + required-`index`) that REJECTS a divergent shape (wrong wrapper key `findings`, wrong per-item key `attributes`, missing/non-int `index`) loudly — pinned by a deterministic test that also documents the current tolerant live behavior. NOT wired onto the live parse (expand-contract); a NOTE + the ADR document the one-line flip + back-out.\n  * Replace the DUPLICATED inline silent-drop (kernel `merge_verifications_by_index` AND the workflow `plan_review_decide`) with ONE shared, structural reshape that returns the SAME tolerant map as today PLUS a contract-violation REPORT (malformed/no-`index` items, duplicate indices, out-of-range indices). In prod the report is LOGGED loudly (ERROR) + counted in verdict coverage (only when >0) — outcomes unchanged.\n  * a deterministic NEGATIVE test that each break (wrong wrapper key, duplicate index, out-of-range index, malformed item) is detected structurally (no grep/glob/substring assertions).\n\n**Phase 3 — code/ticket read-root contract.** Add an OPT-IN `require=` to `resolve_code_root` (raises a clear error when a stage that REQUIRES a root would resolve `None`) — NOT wired onto a live stage (no prod change). A deterministic test pins the #71 cascade (inside an active attested-snapshot context a stage resolves a NON-None root) AND the require-mode loud failure on an unresolved root (no string heuristics).\n\n**Phase 4 — replace ONE brittle grep/glob self-check (advisory COH: AC4 floors at one).** Replace the module-size allowlist check (currently a shell `awk`/`comm`/`grep` in CI with no Python function or unit test) with a structural assertion: a `compute_over_cap_modules()` function + a unit test asserting the allowlist set's structural relationship to the computed over-cap set (containment/equality), not a doc-string lockstep.\n\n### Migration / Rollback (advisory: pre-mortem on the tolerant→strict change)\nExpand-contract by construction: prod stays tolerant (no outcome change); the strict path is test-pinned and flip-ready (a one-line `extra=forbid` enable + threading the distinct reason). Back-out of any added observability is a trivial revert. No live behavioral breaking change ships in this story.\n\n### Callers affected (advisory: acknowledge consumers of the old behavior)\nConsumers of the verifier→decide shape audited: kernel `verify_findings`/`merge_verifications_by_index` and the workflow `plan_review_decide` (the two reshape sites), `pass3_over_findings`/`pass3_decide` (decide), and the existing kernel tests that pin \"no-index item silently dropped\" / \"raising chunk → INDETERMINATE\" (`tests/unit/test_review_kernel.py`) — those tests are extended to also assert the new contract-violation REPORT while keeping the unchanged tolerant map.\n\n## Scope\nIn: the strict contract validator + the shared structural reshape with a loud+counted report, the read-root `require` lever, the seam tests, the OSS research writeup, and migrating ONE high-value brittle grep/glob check. Out: flipping the live parse to strict; rewriting the workflow engine; non-LLM subsystems beyond the read-root contract.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] An OSS-research writeup in `docs/adr/` cites how 3+ actively-maintained projects make LLM-pipeline/structured-output contracts explicit + testable, and records the patterns we adopt and why.\n- [ ] A strict verification-contract validator REJECTS a wrong wrapper key / wrong per-item key / missing-or-non-int `index`, pinned by a deterministic test (the live parse stays tolerant — expand-contract).\n- [ ] A single shared structural reshape replaces BOTH the kernel and the workflow inline silent-drop (no duplicated reshape remains) and returns the same tolerant map PLUS a contract-violation report.\n- [ ] A duplicate / out-of-range / malformed verification index is detected and surfaced as a DISTINCT, loud signal in prod (an ERROR log + a verdict-coverage count surfaced only when >0) — distinct from a genuine `no-verification`; production decisions/verdict are unchanged.\n- [ ] The verification-contract breaks above are covered by a deterministic negative test (no grep/glob/substring assertions).\n- [ ] The code/ticket read-root contract is asserted by a deterministic test that fails if a stage resolves an unresolved/`None` root when one is required (no string heuristics).\n- [ ] At least one brittle grep/glob self-check (the module-size allowlist) is replaced by a structural assertion computing the over-cap set from a function.\n- [ ] No new test relies on grep/glob/substring-contains for a structural contract; `make check` + the suite pass."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782673679893257001,"uuid":"862e3927-7eb6-4ac9-a21c-cb6c0455494e"}